Detailed Working of the System

The proposed system is a gesture-controlled virtual telepresence robot that allows a user to remotely navigate and monitor an environment in real time.

The working of the system is divided into two main modules:

🔹 1. Gesture Control Unit
The user wears a gesture control device equipped with an MPU6050 accelerometer and gyroscope.
The sensor detects hand movements in X, Y, and Z axes.
These movements are processed by the Arduino Nano, which converts them into directional commands.
The commands are transmitted wirelessly using the HC-05 Bluetooth module.
🔹 2. Robot Control Unit
The robot receives signals via another Bluetooth module connected to the Arduino Uno.
Based on received commands:
Motors rotate → robot moves (forward, backward, left, right)
Servo motor rotates → camera direction changes
A Raspberry Pi connected to a camera module streams live video over Wi-Fi.
🔹 3. Video Streaming & VR Experience
The Raspberry Pi captures real-time video using the Pi Camera.
The video is streamed via IP address to a smartphone.
The smartphone is placed inside a VR headset, giving the user an immersive experience.

👉 This creates a feeling as if the user is physically present at the robot’s location.

⚙️ System Architecture Explanation

The system consists of:

Input Layer → Gesture (MPU6050 + Arduino Nano)
Communication Layer → Bluetooth (HC-05)
Control Layer → Arduino Uno
Processing Layer → Raspberry Pi
Output Layer → Motors + Camera + VR Display
🔬 Technical Insight
The accelerometer measures linear motion
The gyroscope measures angular rotation
Sensor data is mapped into directional movement:
Tilt forward → Move forward
Tilt backward → Move backward
Tilt left/right → Turn

👉 This mapping ensures intuitive human-machine interaction.

🔧 Circuit & Component Role Explanation
Arduino Nano → Reads gesture data
Arduino Uno → Controls robot movement
MPU6050 Sensor → Detects motion & orientation
L298N Motor Driver → Drives DC motors
Servo Motor (MG995) → Rotates camera (180° view)
HC-05 Bluetooth Module → Wireless communication
Raspberry Pi → Handles video streaming
Pi Camera → Captures live footage
📊 Performance Analysis
Robot responds in real-time to gesture input
Camera provides live streaming over Wi-Fi
Servo motor allows ~180° rotation
System supports multi-directional movement control
🌍 Real-Time Working Scenario

Example:

A user sitting at home wears a VR headset and controls the robot placed in a remote location (office, hospital, or hazardous area). The robot moves based on hand gestures and streams live video, enabling real-time monitoring and interaction.

